Question: Mr. Jackson‚Äôs fourth-grade class has 27 students. He wants to give each student 2 glue sticks. The glue sticks come in packs of 8. How many packs will Mr. Jackson need to buy so every student can have 2 glue sticks, assuming he can only buy whole packs and he expects to have some extra glue sticks left over?
--------------------------------------------------
Generation:

Mr. Jackson wants to give each of his 27 students 2 glue sticks. Therefore, he needs a total of \(27 \times 2 = 54\) glue sticks. The glue sticks come in packs of 8. To find out how many packs he needed, we divide the total number of glue sticks by the number of glue sticks per pack pack: \(54 \div 8 = 6.75\). Since Mr can only buy whole packs, he will need to round up to the next whole number. Therefore, he will need to buy 7 packs of glue sticks.
</reasoning>
