Question: Jason works as a salesperson at a car dealership.  He needs to sell 15 cars this month to earn a big bonus.  He knows based on historical averages, that for every 25 telephone calls he makes to potential customers, he gets one person to come into the car dealership to look at new cars.  And for every two customers that come into the car dealership, one will buy a car.  Based on these average numbers, how many telephone calls would Jason need to make to sell 15 cars and earn his bonus?
--------------------------------------------------
Generation:

To determine how many telephone calls Jason needs to make to sell 15 cars, we need to follow the given averages step by step.

1. For every 25 telephone calls, Jason gets one customer to come into the dealership.
2. For every two customers that come into the dealership, one will buy a car.

First, we need to find out how many customers are required to buy 15 cars. Since for every two customers, one buys a car, we need:
\[ 15 \text{ cars} \times 2 \text{ customers per car} = 30 \text{ customers} \]

Next, we need to find out how many telephone calls are required to get 30 customers. Since for every 25 telephone calls, Jason gets one customer, we need:
\[ 30 \text{ customers} \times 25 \text{ calls per customer} = 750 \text{ calls} \]

Therefore, Jason needs to make 750 telephone calls to sell 15 cars.

</reasoning>

<answer>
\boxed{750}
</answer><|eot_id|><|endoftext|>
