Question: Mr. Jackson‚Äôs fourth-grade class has 27 students. He wants to give each student 2 glue sticks. The glue sticks come in packs of 8. How many packs will Mr. Jackson need to buy so every student can have 2 glue sticks, assuming he can only buy whole packs and he expects to have some extra glue sticks left over?
--------------------------------------------------
Generation:

To determine how many packs of glue sticks Mr. Jackson needs to buy, we first need to calculate the total number of glue sticks required. Since each of the 27 students will receive 2 glue sticks, we multiply the number of students by the number of glue sticks per student:

\[ 27 \text{ students} \times 2 \text{ glue sticks/student} = 54 \text{ glue sticks} \]

Next, we need to determine how many packs of 8 glue sticks are required to get 54 glue sticks. We do this by dividing the total number of glue sticks by the number of glue sticks per pack:

\[ \frac{54 \text{ glue sticks}}{8 \text{ glue sticks/pack}} = 6.75 \text{ packs} \]

Since Mr. Jackson can only buy whole packs and he expects to have some extra glue sticks left over, he needs to round up to the next whole number. Therefore, he needs to buy 7 packs of glue sticks to ensure that every student can have at least 2 glue sticks.
</answer>
