Question: Mr. Jackson‚Äôs fourth-grade class has 27 students. He wants to give each student 2 glue sticks. The glue sticks come in packs of 8. How many packs will Mr. Jackson need to buy so every student can have 2 glue sticks, assuming he can only buy whole packs and he expects to have some extra glue sticks left over?
--------------------------------------------------
Generation:

1. Mr. Jackson has 27 students.
2. 2 glue sticks are needed for each student.
3. Therefore sticks needed = 27 students * 2 glue sticks/student = 54 glue sticks.
4. Glue sticks come in packs of 8.
5. To find out how many packs are needed, we divide the total number of glue sticks by the number of glue sticks per pack.
6. 54 glue sticks / 8 glue sticks/pack = 6.75 packs.
7. Since Mr. Jackson can only buy whole packs, he needs to round up to the next whole number.
8. Therefore, Mr. Jackson needs to buy 7 packs of glue sticks.
9. To verify, we can calculate how many glue sticks are in 7 packs: 7 packs * 8 glue sticks/pack = 56 glue sticks.
10. Since 56 glue sticks are more than 54, sticks will be left over, but the problem states for the extra glue sticks to be considered, so we still need 7 packs.
</answer>
