Question: Jason works as a salesperson at a car dealership.  He needs to sell 15 cars this month to earn a big bonus.  He knows based on historical averages, that for every 25 telephone calls he makes to potential customers, he gets one person to come into the car dealership to look at new cars.  And for every two customers that come into the car dealership, one will buy a car.  Based on these average numbers, how many telephone calls would Jason need to make to sell 15 cars and earn his bonus?
--------------------------------------------------
Generation:

1. Jason needs to sell 15 cars to earn a bonus.
2. For every 25 telephone calls, he gets one person to come into the dealership.
3. For every two customers that come into the dealership, one will buy a car.
4. Therefore, for every 25 telephone calls, half of the customers will buy a car.
5. To sell 15 cars, he needs 15 customers to buy a car.
6. Since half of the customers will buy a car, he needs \( 15 \times 2 = 30 \) customers to come into the dealership.
7. For every 25 telephone calls, 1 customer comes into the dealership.
8. Therefore, to get 30 customers, he needs to make \( 30 \times 25 = 750 \) telephone calls.
</reasoning>
<answer>
\boxed{750}
</answer><|eot_id|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|><|endoftext|>
