Question: Mr. Jackson‚Äôs fourth-grade class has 27 students. He wants to give each student 2 glue sticks. The glue sticks come in packs of 8. How many packs will Mr. Jackson need to buy so every student can have 2 glue sticks, assuming he can only buy whole packs and he expects to have some extra glue sticks left over?
--------------------------------------------------
Generation:

1. Mr. Jackson has 27 students in his class.
2. He wants to give each student 2 glue sticks.
3. Therefore, the total number of glue sticks needed is \(27 \times 2 = 54\).
4. Glue sticks come in packs of 8.
5. To find out how many packs are needed, we divide the total number of glue sticks by the number of glue sticks per pack: \(54 \div 8\).
6. Performing the division gives \( \div 8 = 6.75\).
7. Since Mr. Jackson can only buy whole packs, he needs to round up to the next whole number.
8. Therefore, Mr. Jackson needs to buy 7 packs of glue sticks.
9. To verify, 7 packs of \(8 \times 7 = 56\) glue sticks, which is more than 54.
10. Since  expects to have some extra glue sticks left over, 7 packs will enough.
11. Thus, Mr. Jackson will buy 7 packs.
</answer>
