Question: Mr. Jackson‚Äôs fourth-grade class has 27 students. He wants to give each student 2 glue sticks. The glue sticks come in packs of 8. How many packs will Mr. Jackson need to buy so every student can have 2 glue sticks, assuming he can only buy whole packs and he expects to have some extra glue sticks left over?
--------------------------------------------------
Generation:

1. Mr. Jackson has 27 students
22. He wants to give each student 2 glue sticks.
3. Therefore, the total number of glue sticks needed is \(27 \times 2 = 54\).
4. Glue sticks come in packs of 8.
5. To find out how many packs are needed, we divide the total number of glue sticks by the number of glue sticks per pack pack.
6. Calculate \(54 \div 8 = 6.75\).
7. Since Mr. Jackson can only buy whole packs, he will need to round up to the next whole number.
8. Therefore, Mr. Jackson needs to buy 7 packs of glue sticks.
9. To verify, we can calculate the number of glue sticks in 7 packs: \(7 \times 8 = 56\).
10. Since 56 glue sticks are more than 54, Mr will Jackson will have some extra glue sticks left over, but the question asks for the number of packs needed, not the extra glue sticks in the packs.
</answer>
