Question: Mr. Jackson‚Äôs fourth-grade class has 27 students. He wants to give each student 2 glue sticks. The glue sticks come in packs of 8. How many packs will Mr. Jackson need to buy so every student can have 2 glue sticks, assuming he can only buy whole packs and he expects to have some extra glue sticks left over?
--------------------------------------------------
Generation:

1. Mr. Jackson‚Äôs fourth-grade class has 27 students.
2. He wants to give each student 2 glue sticks.
3. Therefore, the total number of glue sticks needed is \(27 \times 2 = 54\).
4. The glue sticks come in packs of 8.
5. To find out how many packs Mr. Jackson we need to buy, we divide the total number of glue sticks needed by the number of glue sticks per pack.
6. The calculation is \(54 \div 8\).
7. Since Mr Jackson can only buy whole packs, we need to round up to the next whole number.
8. \(54 \div 8 = 6.75\).
9. Therefore, Mr. Jackson needs to buy 7 packs to have sticks for all students.
10. To verify, we7 packstimes 8 glue sticks per pack = 56 glue sticks.
11. Since 56 glue sticks are more than 54, Mr. Jackson will need 7 packs to have enough glue sticks.
