Question: Jason works as a salesperson at a car dealership.  He needs to sell 15 cars this month to earn a big bonus.  He knows based on historical averages, that for every 25 telephone calls he makes to potential customers, he gets one person to come into the car dealership to look at new cars.  And for every two customers that come into the car dealership, one will buy a car.  Based on these average numbers, how many telephone calls would Jason need to make to sell 15 cars and earn his bonus?
--------------------------------------------------
Generation:

1. Jason needs to sell 15 cars to earn a big bonus this month.
2. For every 25 telephone calls he makes to potential customers, he gets one person to come into the car dealership to look at new cars.
3. For every two customers that come into the car dealership, one will buy a car.
4. Therefore, for every 25 telephone calls, one will buy a car.
5. To sell 15 cars, he needs 15 customers to buy a car.
6. Since every two customers come into the car dealership, one will buy a car, to get 15 customers to buy a car, he needs \(15 \times 2 = 30\) customers to come into the car dealership.
7. For every 25 telephone calls, one customer comes into the car dealership, so to get 30 customers to come into the car dealership, he needs \(30 \times 25 = 750\) telephone calls.
8. Therefore, Jason needs to make 750 telephone calls to earn his bonus.
</answer>
<answer>
\boxed{750}
</answer><|eot_id|>
